  "response": "That's a really tough question! What one person finds incredibly depressing, another might find cathartic or even beautiful. Also, what makes a song \"depressing\" can vary \u2013 is it the lyrics, the melody, the artist's delivery, or a combination of everything?\n\nHowever, some songs are frequently mentioned in discussions about depressing music:\n\n*   **\"Gloomy Sunday\" by Billie Holiday (or Rezso Seress):** Famously known as the \"Hungarian Suicide Song,\" it's associated with numerous suicides.\n\n*   **\"Hurt\" by Johnny Cash (originally by Nine Inch Nails):** Cash's weathered voice and the song's themes of regret and pain make it incredibly powerful.\n\n*   **\"Yesterday\" by The Beatles:** A simple, melancholic tune about lost love that resonates with many.\n\n*   **\"Tears in Heaven\" by Eric Clapton:** Written after the tragic death of his young son, it's a raw expression of grief.\n\n*   **\"The Sound of Silence\" by Simon & Garfunkel:** Its themes of isolation and lack of communication can be deeply unsettling.\n\n*   **\"Mad World\" by Gary Jules (originally by Tears for Fears):** Its stark piano arrangement and lyrics about the absurdity of life can be quite depressing.\n\n*   **\"Eleanor Rigby\" by The Beatles:** A song about loneliness and isolation, portraying characters who live and die unnoticed.\n\nUltimately, the most depressing song is subjective and depends on your personal experiences and preferences.",
